'''Liberato Gianpaolo Cacace''' ({{IPAc-en|k|ə|ˈ|k|ɑː|tʃ|i}} {{respell|kə|KAH|chee}};<ref>{{cite AV media |author=New Zealand Football |title=Ask The Squad {{!}} Liberato Cacace & Elijah Just |date=8 November 2021 |url=https://www.https/ |access-date=16 January 2022 |url-status=dead |via=[[YouTube]] |archive-date=19 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130819141428/http://https/ }}</ref> born 27 September 2000) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left-back]] for {{English football updater|Wrexham}} club [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]] and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/123695879/21stcentury-sports-stars-five-kiwis-just-getting-started-on-the-international-stage |title=21st-century sports stars: Five Kiwis just getting started on the international stage |work=Stuff |access-date=1 January 2021}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Island Bay===
As a youth, Cacace played for [[Island Bay United]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Island Bay United Association Football Club|url=https://www.facebook.com/IslandBayIBUAFC/posts/1155894371161553|website=Facebook|access-date=6 November 2016}}</ref> and was also a representative player of [[Capital Football (New Zealand)|Capital Football]] for two years in their 1999 squad.<ref name="youth">{{cite web|title=Club Garibaldi News|url=http://www.clubgaribaldi.org.nz/assets/Documents/Newsletters/Club-Newsletter-2012-March.pdf|website=Club Garibaldi|access-date=2 February 2018}}</ref> He was chosen by former [[Wellington Phoenix]] and [[New Zealand men's national football team|All Whites]] coach [[Ricki Herbert]] to be part of his junior elite academy.<ref name="youth" />

Cacace also played for his school team at [[St. Patrick's College, Wellington|St Patrick's College]] in [[Wellington]], alongside South Sudan international [[Manyumow Achol]]. Cacace helped his college team win the Wellington Premier Youth football league, scoring in the 2–1 final against [[Hutt International Boys' School]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hyslop|first1=Liam|title=St Pat's Town rejoice in unexpected football triumph|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/sport/college-sport/96259992/st-pats-town-rejoice-in-unexpected-football-triumph|access-date=2 February 2018|publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=29 August 2017}}</ref>

===Wellington Phoenix Reserves===
Cacace started playing for the [[Wellington Phoenix FC Reserves|Wellington Phoenix Reserves]] in the [[New Zealand Football Championship]] in the [[2016–17 New Zealand Football Championship|2016–17]] season, making eight appearances, including four starts.<ref name="soccerway">{{Soccerway|liberato-cacace/467149}}</ref>

During the winter season, Cacace played with Wellington Phoenix feeder club [[Wellington United]] in the local [[Central Premier League|Central League]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Singh|first1=Anendra|title=Football: Rovers succumb heavily against Wellington United in Napier|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/hawkes-bay-today/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=1503460&objectid=11843719|access-date=2 February 2018|publisher=Hawkes Bay Today|date=23 April 2017}}</ref>

===Wellington Phoenix===
On 2 February 2018, Cacace made his debut for the senior side, coming on as a substitute in a 4–0 defeat against [[Sydney FC]] in the [[A-League]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rollo|first1=Phillip|title=Sydney FC swat Wellington aside as Phoenix punished for costly mistakes|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/101127648/sydney-fc-swat-wellington-aside-as-phoenix-punished-for-costly-mistakes|publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=2 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Wellington Phoenix Squad: Round 20 v Sydney FC|url=https://www.wellingtonphoenix.com/news/wellington-phoenix-squad-round-20-v-sydney-fc|website=Wellington Phoenix|date=February 2018 |access-date=2 February 2018}}</ref> Following the end of the [[2017–18 A-League]] season, and having made seven appearances for the club, Cacace signed a three-year professional contract with Wellington Phoenix.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/104035891/wellington-phoenix-bring-back-andrew-durante-and-liberato-cacace-for-coming-season|title=Wellington Phoenix bring back Andrew Durante and Liberato Cacace for coming season|work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=18 May 2018}}</ref>

In the [[2018–19 A-League|2018–19 season]], following the departure of [[Scott Galloway (soccer)|Scott Galloway]] and injury to [[Tom Doyle]], Cacace became the first-choice [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left-back]] under new manager [[Marko Rudan]], one month after his 18th birthday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/115851145/liberato-cacaces-contract-leaves-wellington-phoenix-in-a-tricky-situation|title=Liberato Cacace's contract leaves Wellington Phoenix in a tricky situation|website=Stuff}}</ref> Cacace scored his maiden [[A-League]] goal against [[Central Coast Mariners]] in an 8-2 victory on 9 March 2019, becoming the club's youngest ever goalscorer at 18 years and 163 days.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rollo|first1=Phillip|title=Wellington Phoenix climb into top-four after thumping Central Coast Mariners 8-2|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/111162587/wellington-phoenix-climb-into-topfour-after-thumping-central-coast-mariners-82|publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=9 March 2019}}</ref> After playing more minutes than any other Wellington Phoenix player that season, Cacace won the club's Young Player of the Year award ahead of fellow starter [[Sarpreet Singh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wellingtonphoenix.com/news/wellington-phoenix-players-recognised-new-zealand-football-awards-2019|title=Wellington Phoenix Players Recognised At New Zealand Football Awards 2019|date=28 July 2019|website=Wellington Phoenix}}</ref>

The following season, Cacace established himself as one of Wellington's most important players, with captain [[Steven Taylor (footballer)|Steven Taylor]] calling him "the best left-back in the league without a shadow of a doubt".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/120042912/wellington-phoenix-rising-star-liberato-cacace-has-premier-league-potential|title=Wellington Phoenix rising star Liberato Cacace has Premier League potential|website=Stuff}}</ref> On 8 March 2020, Cacace played his 50th game for Wellington Phoenix against Central Coast Mariners, the youngest player in the club's history to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/120009171/young-star-liberato-cacace-to-play-milestone-50th-aleague-game-for-wellington-phoenix|title=Young star Liberato Cacace to play milestone 50th A-League game for Wellington Phoenix|website=Stuff}}</ref>

===Sint-Truiden===
After a stellar season with the [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]],<ref name="Stellar">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Wellington Phoenix rising star Liberato Cacace joins Belgian club Sint-Truiden |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/122535626/wellington-phoenix-rising-star-liberato-cacace-joins-belgian-club-sinttruiden |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=27 August 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Cacace signed a three-year contract with [[Sint-Truidense V.V.|Sint-Truiden]] for an estimated transfer fee of around €1.2 million.<ref name="STVV">{{cite news |title=STVV legt ruim miljoen euro neer voor Nieuw-Zeelander - Khammas van Genk naar W.-Beveren - Plzen denkt aan Krmencik |url=https://www.hln.be/sport/voetbal/transfer-talk-stvv-legt-ruim-miljoen-euro-neer-voor-nieuw-zeelander-khammas-van-genk-naar-w-beveren-plzen-denkt-aan-krmencik~a98c268b/ |publisher=Het Laatste Nieuws |date=28 August 2020}}</ref>

===Empoli===
On 31 January 2022, Cacace joined [[Italy|Italian]] [[Serie A]] club [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]] on loan, with a conditional obligation to buy.<ref>{{cite press release|publisher=[[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]]|url=https://empolifc.com/liberato-cacace-e-dellempoli/|title=Liberato Cacace è dell'Empoli|date=31 January 2022|access-date=31 January 2022|language=it}}</ref> The conditions were fulfilled and Empoli purchased the rights on 17 June 2022.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tecce|first1=Filippo|publisher=Empoli|url=https://empolifc.com/esercitato-il-riscatto-per-liberato-cacace-e-petar-stojanovic/|title=Esercitato il riscatto per Liberato Cacace e Petar Stojanovic|work=Empoli FC|date=17 June 2022|access-date=2 July 2022|language=it|archive-date=18 June 2022|archive-url=https://archive.today/20220618081608/https://empolifc.com/esercitato-il-riscatto-per-liberato-cacace-e-petar-stojanovic/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Across four seasons, Cacace made 76 Serie A appearances and scored 2 goals, and overall including other competitions made 83 appearances.

===Wrexham===
On 18 July 2025, it was announced Cacace joined newly-promoted [[EFL Championship]] club [[Wrexham A.F.C|Wrexham]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Wrexham AFC|url=https://www.wrexhamafc.co.uk/news/2025/july/18/signed---wrexham-sign-liberato-cacace-from-empoli|title=Wrexham sign Liberato Cacace from Empoli|date=18 July 2025|access-date=18 July 2025|language=en}}</ref> On 9 January 2026, Cacace scored his first goal for Wrexham in a 3–3 draw in the [[2025-26 FA Cup#Third round|FA Cup]] against [[Premier League]] side  [[Nottingham Forest]]. Wrexham would go on to win 4–3 in a [[penalty shootout]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360922707/liberato-cacace-scores-first-goal-wrexham-who-beat-nottingham-forest-penalties-fa-cup|title=Liberato Cacace scores first goal for Wrexham who beat Nottingham Forest on penalties in FA Cup|date=10 January 2026|access-date=10 January 2026|website=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]}}</ref>

==International career==

=== Youth ===
Cacace was part of the [[New Zealand national under-17 football team|New Zealand U17]] team that won the [[2017 OFC U-17 Championship]], where he scored one goal. This meant that the team qualified for the [[2017 FIFA U-17 World Cup]] in India. Cacace then played at the FIFA U-17 World Cup,<ref>{{cite web|title=New Zealand U-17 coach Danny Hay has delivered a clear message to his squad ahead of the FIFA U-17 World Cup in India|url=http://www.nzfootball.co.nz/hay-names-balanced-wc-squad/|publisher=New Zealand Football|language=en|access-date=21 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923195256/http://www.nzfootball.co.nz/hay-names-balanced-wc-squad/|archive-date=23 September 2017}}</ref> making his World Cup debut in the 1–1 draw with [[Turkey national under-17 football team|Turkey U17]],<ref>{{cite web|title=New Zealand v Turkey Match Report|url=https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=275931/match=300394708/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926190946/http://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=275931/match=300394708/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 September 2017|website=[[FIFA.com]]|access-date=2 February 2018}}</ref> before starting again in a 4–2 loss to [[Paraguay national under-17 football team|Paraguay U17]]<ref>{{cite web|title=New Zealand v Paraguay Match Report|url=https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=275931/match=300394704/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926190953/http://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=275931/match=300394704/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 September 2017|website=[[FIFA.com]]|access-date=2 February 2018}}</ref> and a 3–1 loss to [[Mali national under-17 football team|Mali U17]].<ref>{{cite web|title=New Zealand v Mali Match Report|url=https://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=275931/match=300394712/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926190855/http://www.fifa.com/u17worldcup/matches/round=275931/match=300394712/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 September 2017|website=[[FIFA.com]]|access-date=2 February 2018}}</ref>

Cacace scored the opening goal at the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament – Group B|2020 Summer Olympics]] in [[New Zealand national under-23 football team|New Zealand]]'s 3–2 loss to [[Honduras national under-23 football team|Honduras]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |date=25 July 2021 |title=Defensive howler costs OlyWhites in loss to Honduras at Tokyo Olympics |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/olympics/125857088/defensive-howler-costs-olywhites-in-loss-to-honduras-at-tokyo-olympics |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |language=en}}</ref>

=== Senior ===
Cacace was selected to join the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]] squad in the [[2018 Intercontinental Cup (India)|2018 Intercontinental Cup]] held in India.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Voerman|first1=Andrew|title=Nothing changes for schoolboy footballer Liberato Cacace despite his rapid rise|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/104237446/nothing-changes-for-schoolboy-footballer-liberato-cacace-despite-his-rapid-rise|access-date=6 June 2018|publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=27 May 2018}}</ref> He made his All Whites debut in Mumbai on 5 June 2018 against [[Chinese Taipei national football team|Chinese Taipei]], in a 1–0 victory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Football: All Whites win scrappy encounter over Chinese Taipei|url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=12065233|access-date=6 June 2018|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=6 June 2018}}</ref>

On 25 June 2021, Cacace was called up to the New Zealand squad for the delayed [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622| title= Squads named for Tokyo 2020| date= 25 June 2021| publisher= [[New Zealand Football]]| language= en| access-date= 25 June 2021| archive-date= 25 June 2021| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20210625021412/https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/105080?newsfeedId=1275622| url-status= dead}}</ref>

Cacace scored against [[Tahiti national football team|Tahiti]] in a 1–0 win in the semi-finals of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=All Whites reach Oceania Qualifiers final |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/nzfootball/newsarticle/113929?newsfeedid=1223399 |access-date=28 March 2022 |website=nzfootball.co.nz}}</ref>

In the [[2024 OFC Men's Nations Cup|2024 OFC Nations Cup]], Cacace was named as captain where he guided New Zealand to lift the trophy on 30 June 2024.

==Personal life==
Cacace was born in [[Wellington]] to an Italian father and a New Zealand mother of Italian descent. His father Antonio arrived in the country in 1992 from [[Massa Lubrense]], a small commune in [[province of Naples|Naples]], and operates ''La Bella Italia'', an Italian restaurant located in [[Petone]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rollo|first1=Phillip|title=Wellington boy Liberato Cacace makes Phoenix debut at 17|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/101161812/wellington-boy-liberato-cacace-makes-phoenix-debut-at-17|access-date=6 June 2018|publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=4 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/photograph/448/antonio-cacace|title=Antonio Cacace|first1=Shirley|last1=Williams|first2=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|last2=Taonga|website=teara.govt.nz}}</ref> He attended [[St Patrick's College, Kilbirnie, Wellington|St Patrick's College]].<ref name="school">{{cite news|last1=Rollo|first1=Phillip|title=Back to school for Wellington Phoenix teenager Liberato Cacace|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/103327515/back-to-school-for-wellington-phoenix-teenager-liberato-cacace|access-date=26 April 2018|publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]]|date=25 April 2018}}</ref>

Cacace supports his father's hometown team, [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]].<ref>{{Cite web
